What is an AppBar?
Simple definition: An AppBar is the top bar of your app screen. It's like the header/title bar you see at the top of most mobile apps.

Think of it like: The blue bar at the top of the Facebook app, or the bar at the top of your Gmail app that says "Inbox" and has a search icon.

Where Does It Go?
An AppBar goes inside a Scaffold using the appBar property:

Why? Because the Scaffold is like the main structure of your screen (like a house frame), and the AppBar is the roof/top part.

|Summary Table (For Quick Reference)|

Part	          Location               Common Use	              Code
leading	        Top-Left	             Menu/Back button	        leading: IconButton(...)
title	          Top-Center/Left	       Screen name	            title: Text('Home')
actions	        Top-Right	             Search/Share/More	      actions: [IconButton(...)]
bottom	        Below title	           Tabs	                    bottom: TabBar(...)
flexibleSpace  	Behind everything	     Background color/image	  flexibleSpace: Container(...)

3 Rules for Beginners
1) Always put AppBar inside Scaffold.appBar (not outside)

2) If you use a Drawer, you don't need to manually add a menu button - Flutter adds it automatically

3) If you're on a secondary screen, you don't need to manually add a back button - Flutter adds it automatically



